1
00:00:00,672 --> 00:00:02,205
Previously on Longmire...

2
00:00:02,395 --> 00:00:04,158
***

3
00:00:04,278 --> 00:00:05,803
I promised Henry I'd go get

4
00:00:05,923 --> 00:00:07,701
***

5
00:00:08,746 --> 00:00:09,937
***

6
00:00:10,057 --> 00:00:10,818
Cady...

7
00:00:10,938 --> 00:00:13,765
***

8
00:00:13,885 --> 00:00:15,589
Is it because of me?

9
00:00:15,709 --> 00:00:19,758
***

10
00:00:21,270 --> 00:00:23,364
Hey, Walt. You won.

11
00:00:23,655 --> 00:00:26,176
- What?
- The election.

12
00:00:32,103 --> 00:00:35,139
[ Monitor beeping ]

13
00:01:27,358 --> 00:01:29,993
[ Exhales deeply ]

14
00:01:53,685 --> 00:01:55,752
Cady is awake.

15
00:02:05,730 --> 00:02:07,865
[ Indistinct conversations ]

16
00:02:12,670 --> 00:02:16,240
[ Monitor beeping ]

17
00:02:16,341 --> 00:02:19,643
Dad.

18
00:02:19,744 --> 00:02:21,745
You look like hell.

19
00:02:28,786 --> 00:02:30,854
You scared me, punk.

20
00:02:33,658 --> 00:02:35,325
[ Sighs ]

21
00:02:45,036 --> 00:02:48,906
Ah, so, any news?

22
00:02:49,007 --> 00:02:51,108
Actually, uh...
yeah.

23
00:02:51,209 --> 00:02:53,677
Looks like my daughter's
out of the woods.

24
00:02:53,778 --> 00:02:56,179
Well, that's great.
Yeah.

25
00:02:56,281 --> 00:02:58,949
Uh, sorry, um,
I don't think you guys have met.

26
00:02:59,050 --> 00:03:01,718
Troy, this is Sheriff Longmire.

27
00:03:01,819 --> 00:03:03,554
You're number 44.

28
00:03:03,655 --> 00:03:05,589
They still have your jersey

29
00:03:05,690 --> 00:03:07,291
in a trophy case at school.

30
00:03:07,392 --> 00:03:10,227
Thing's almost an antique.

31
00:03:10,328 --> 00:03:12,129
Your dad tells me
you're a pretty good player.

32
00:03:12,130 --> 00:03:14,998
[ Chuckles ]
I'm a running back.

33
00:03:15,099 --> 00:03:17,200
And hopefully, we'll have him
on the field soon.

34
00:03:17,302 --> 00:03:19,269
Doctors have finally
figured out that

35
00:03:19,370 --> 00:03:22,839
Troy has some kind of
degenerative muscle disease.

36
00:03:22,941 --> 00:03:24,741
Wasting sickness, they call it.

37
00:03:24,842 --> 00:03:26,176
Not the best of diagnosis,

38
00:03:26,277 --> 00:03:28,812
but it's a step
in the right direction.

39
00:03:28,913 --> 00:03:30,681
At least we know now
what to fight.

40
00:03:30,782 --> 00:03:32,215
Nurse: Sheriff?

41
00:03:32,317 --> 00:03:33,951
There's a phone call for you.

42
00:03:34,052 --> 00:03:35,686
Excuse me.
Sure.

43
00:03:39,691 --> 00:03:41,892
Hello?
Vic: Hey, Walt.

44
00:03:41,993 --> 00:03:44,695
Ruby told me that Cady's awake.
I'm so glad.

45
00:03:44,796 --> 00:03:46,763
Thanks, Vic. Uh, yeah,
she's doing better.

46
00:03:46,864 --> 00:03:48,031
Is that why you called?

47
00:03:48,132 --> 00:03:50,133
[ Sighs ]
It's not the only reason,

48
00:03:50,234 --> 00:03:52,736
but, uh, I shouldn't have
bothered you.

49
00:03:52,837 --> 00:03:54,271
What is it, Vic?
It's nothing.

50
00:03:54,372 --> 00:03:56,106
Uh, you should
stay there with Cady.

51
00:03:56,207 --> 00:03:58,909
She's resting. And besides,
I've been here for hours.

52
00:03:59,010 --> 00:04:00,970
She could use a break
from her dad hanging around.

53
00:04:01,012 --> 00:04:02,613
Ruby can stay with her a while.

54
00:04:02,714 --> 00:04:03,814
What's up?

55
00:04:03,915 --> 00:04:05,148
This is Connor Redding.

56
00:04:05,249 --> 00:04:06,883
28 years old.

57
00:04:06,985 --> 00:04:08,251
He's a game warden.

58
00:04:08,353 --> 00:04:10,921
This entire area
was part of his patrol.

59
00:04:11,022 --> 00:04:14,191
He was found by bird watchers.

60
00:04:14,292 --> 00:04:16,059
Hey, sheriff.

61
00:04:16,160 --> 00:04:18,028
I gave fish and game
the heads up.

62
00:04:18,129 --> 00:04:19,763
This is Devin Gaines.

63
00:04:19,864 --> 00:04:22,132
Appreciate you
coming down so fast.

64
00:04:22,233 --> 00:04:24,201
I gather
you worked with the victim.

65
00:04:24,302 --> 00:04:26,269
Yeah, I, uh, hired him.

66
00:04:26,371 --> 00:04:28,672
Connor and I were pretty close.

67
00:04:28,773 --> 00:04:30,674
He came out here from Alaska

68
00:04:30,775 --> 00:04:32,876
about a year ago with his wife.

69
00:04:32,977 --> 00:04:35,712
They've got a baby girl.

70
00:04:35,813 --> 00:04:37,781
She's only 2.

71
00:04:37,882 --> 00:04:40,517
Looks like he took
two stab wounds to the chest.

72
00:04:40,618 --> 00:04:43,053
Deep cuts. Probably from
a hunting knife.

73
00:04:43,154 --> 00:04:46,657
What about our other victim?

74
00:04:46,758 --> 00:04:48,191
The elk?

75
00:04:48,292 --> 00:04:50,227
Elk season's a month off.

76
00:04:50,328 --> 00:04:52,996
Means this is also a murder.

77
00:04:53,097 --> 00:04:55,565
Considering all the hunting
we got out here,

78
00:04:55,667 --> 00:04:58,268
it's pretty easy for game
wardens to make enemies fast.

79
00:04:58,369 --> 00:05:01,038
Most hunters
respect what we do,

80
00:05:01,139 --> 00:05:02,739
but there are always
a few idiots

81
00:05:02,840 --> 00:05:04,641
who don't like
having to abide by rules.

82
00:05:04,742 --> 00:05:06,777
Anyone in particular you know?

83
00:05:06,878 --> 00:05:09,579
I spent a month trying to catch
this one poacher.

84
00:05:09,681 --> 00:05:11,848
He's been killing a lot of elk
out of season

85
00:05:11,949 --> 00:05:14,217
and taking their heads
as some kind of trophy.

86
00:05:14,318 --> 00:05:17,220
This looks like his handiwork.

87
00:05:17,321 --> 00:05:19,256
I've searched the area.

88
00:05:19,357 --> 00:05:21,091
Guy's got serious skills.

89
00:05:21,192 --> 00:05:23,960
Knows where to go,
how to cover his tracks.

90
00:05:24,062 --> 00:05:26,797
Looks like Connor probably, uh,
caught him in the act, so...

91
00:05:26,898 --> 00:05:29,666
Wait, so, a guy gets caught
killing elk out of season

92
00:05:29,767 --> 00:05:31,168
and resorts to murder?

93
00:05:31,269 --> 00:05:33,136
It just seems like
a lot of risk

94
00:05:33,237 --> 00:05:34,971
to put a head on a wall.

95
00:05:35,073 --> 00:05:37,808
If the killer was looking
to mount the elk head,

96
00:05:37,909 --> 00:05:40,610
he'd need to do it quickly.

97
00:05:46,184 --> 00:05:49,386
[ Air hissing ]

98
00:05:53,891 --> 00:05:55,625
Nice job.

99
00:05:55,727 --> 00:05:57,627
Oh, hey. Yeah.

100
00:05:57,729 --> 00:06:00,263
You'd never know
they weren't swimming.

101
00:06:00,364 --> 00:06:02,933
I got more for sale
if you're looking to buy.

102
00:06:03,034 --> 00:06:05,936
Actually, I'm more interested
in elk today.

103
00:06:06,037 --> 00:06:08,905
Anyone come in recently
to have a head mounted?

104
00:06:09,006 --> 00:06:11,742
Well, they'd have to be
pretty dumb to do so.

105
00:06:11,843 --> 00:06:13,944
I keep a close eye
on the calendar.

106
00:06:14,045 --> 00:06:15,579
Anybody comes in with an elk

107
00:06:15,680 --> 00:06:17,280
even a day before
the season opens,

108
00:06:17,381 --> 00:06:19,549
I put in a call
to fish and game.

109
00:06:19,650 --> 00:06:22,185
You could risk losing your whole
business working with poachers.

110
00:06:22,286 --> 00:06:24,688
I'm sure there are some
taxidermists who don't mind,

111
00:06:24,789 --> 00:06:26,223
if they're
offered enough money.

112
00:06:26,324 --> 00:06:28,258
All the other shops
are closed till the fall,

113
00:06:28,359 --> 00:06:31,061
when elk and deer season's
opened.

114
00:06:31,162 --> 00:06:33,897
That's when we make most of
our money mounting heads.

115
00:06:33,998 --> 00:06:35,732
You mind if we
finish this outside?

116
00:06:35,833 --> 00:06:38,668
I want to let this guy dry
out in the open air.

117
00:06:38,770 --> 00:06:40,036
That works.

118
00:06:40,138 --> 00:06:41,905
Summers are tough.

119
00:06:42,006 --> 00:06:45,542
Not a huge market for 13-inch
rainbows, as you can see.

120
00:06:45,643 --> 00:06:48,011
But I got a firewood business

121
00:06:48,112 --> 00:06:50,947
that lets me stay open
year-round.

122
00:06:51,048 --> 00:06:52,682
Well, keep an eye out
for me, Lee.

123
00:06:52,784 --> 00:06:54,704
Anyone brings in an elk head,
you give me a call.

124
00:06:54,719 --> 00:06:55,852
Yeah, will do, sheriff.

125
00:06:55,953 --> 00:06:57,621
Oh, hey.

126
00:06:57,722 --> 00:06:59,156
I've got a broken deer head
back at the station,

127
00:06:59,257 --> 00:07:00,824
and I'm not sure
it can be fixed,

128
00:07:00,925 --> 00:07:02,526
but I'd appreciate it
if you'd take a look for me.

129
00:07:02,627 --> 00:07:04,294
Oh, I'd be happy to.

130
00:07:04,395 --> 00:07:05,996
Hey, Lee.

131
00:07:06,097 --> 00:07:07,964
Hey, I just picked up
a big load of scrap wood.

132
00:07:08,065 --> 00:07:10,834
Figured you might be able to
sell some of it for kindling.

133
00:07:10,935 --> 00:07:13,670
[ Chuckles ]

134
00:07:23,981 --> 00:07:25,415
Hey, Cady.

135
00:07:29,353 --> 00:07:31,121
Do I know you?

136
00:07:31,222 --> 00:07:33,223
I'm sorry.

137
00:07:33,324 --> 00:07:36,293
I've had a head injury. I don't
remember certain people.

138
00:07:40,298 --> 00:07:42,933
[ Chuckles ]
I'm sorry.

139
00:07:43,034 --> 00:07:44,134
Ow.

140
00:07:44,235 --> 00:07:45,869
I'm sorry, it was too good.

141
00:07:45,970 --> 00:07:47,804
[ Laughs ]

142
00:07:47,905 --> 00:07:50,173
I like to think
I'm kind of hard to forget.

143
00:07:50,274 --> 00:07:52,209
Oh.

144
00:07:52,310 --> 00:07:54,044
How you feeling?

145
00:07:54,145 --> 00:07:55,579
Okay.

146
00:07:55,680 --> 00:07:57,214
But they have me
doped up to the gills,

147
00:07:57,315 --> 00:08:00,650
and I really haven't
tried moving around yet, so...

148
00:08:00,751 --> 00:08:02,686
Do you, uh,

149
00:08:02,787 --> 00:08:04,621
remember
anything about the accident?

150
00:08:04,722 --> 00:08:06,990
You know how you got
that flat tire?

151
00:08:07,091 --> 00:08:09,993
Honestly, I-I don't remember
anything from that day.

152
00:08:10,094 --> 00:08:11,761
It's a total blank.

153
00:08:11,863 --> 00:08:12,796
[ Sniffs ]

154
00:08:12,897 --> 00:08:15,198
Um, is your, uh...

155
00:08:15,299 --> 00:08:16,800
is your dad around?

156
00:08:16,901 --> 00:08:19,536
No. He got called into work,
thank God.

157
00:08:19,637 --> 00:08:22,239
He's been great --
it's just hard to rest

158
00:08:22,340 --> 00:08:25,308
when someone is staring at you.

159
00:08:28,012 --> 00:08:30,981
Oh, he got called into work,

160
00:08:31,082 --> 00:08:33,216
which means that he won.

161
00:08:33,317 --> 00:08:35,185
It was close.
Really?

162
00:08:35,286 --> 00:08:37,220
[ Both chuckle ]
Mm-hmm. Really close.

163
00:08:37,321 --> 00:08:39,222
You're not wearing
your uniform.

164
00:08:39,323 --> 00:08:40,991
Does that mean you were fired?

165
00:08:41,092 --> 00:08:43,059
He hasn't asked me to leave,

166
00:08:43,160 --> 00:08:44,261
if that's
what you're wondering.

167
00:08:44,362 --> 00:08:47,163
Have you asked him to stay?

168
00:08:52,003 --> 00:08:53,770
[ Sighs ]

169
00:08:55,740 --> 00:08:59,009
Did you dress your wounds?

170
00:08:59,110 --> 00:09:01,077
Yeah, I used some of that
men-wake you gave me.

171
00:09:01,178 --> 00:09:02,913
Thanks. I'm fine.

172
00:09:03,014 --> 00:09:04,814
It will leave a mark.

173
00:09:04,916 --> 00:09:07,050
Mm. Yeah,
I figured it might.

174
00:09:07,151 --> 00:09:08,652
Henry.

175
00:09:08,753 --> 00:09:10,520
Walt.

176
00:09:10,621 --> 00:09:13,023
Whoa.
You go surfing?

177
00:09:13,124 --> 00:09:15,592
Very funny.

178
00:09:15,693 --> 00:09:18,061
Uh, you heard stories about
anyone poaching any elk lately?

179
00:09:18,162 --> 00:09:20,230
Well, if I had,
you'd have heard about it.

180
00:09:20,331 --> 00:09:23,533
Of course, if I had it my way,
they'd be shot on sight.

181
00:09:23,634 --> 00:09:25,568
Poachers are
the lowest of the low.

182
00:09:25,670 --> 00:09:28,138
They got no regard
for natural law.

183
00:09:28,239 --> 00:09:29,873
There's a time to kill things

184
00:09:29,974 --> 00:09:31,574
and a time to let them thrive.

185
00:09:31,676 --> 00:09:33,543
Thank goodness
you have appointed yourself

186
00:09:33,644 --> 00:09:35,011
the protector of natural law.

187
00:09:35,968 --> 00:09:39,516
Natural law isn't my usual
jurisdiction, but, uh...

188
00:09:39,617 --> 00:09:41,885
this poacher
didn't stop with the elk.

189
00:09:41,986 --> 00:09:44,087
He also killed a game warden.

190
00:09:44,188 --> 00:09:46,656
Which one?
Connor Redding.

191
00:09:46,757 --> 00:09:48,692
Aw, shoot.

192
00:09:48,793 --> 00:09:50,593
Young kid. Good guy.

193
00:09:50,695 --> 00:09:52,996
What was this poacher
after? Meat?

194
00:09:53,097 --> 00:09:54,531
Don't think so.

195
00:09:54,632 --> 00:09:57,267
Head was gone,
body was left behind.

196
00:09:57,368 --> 00:09:59,536
Looks like whoever it was
was after a trophy.

197
00:09:59,637 --> 00:10:01,604
Not much of a trophy.

198
00:10:01,706 --> 00:10:04,641
This time of year, the antlers
are barely starting to grow.

199
00:10:04,742 --> 00:10:07,043
No. Most head hunters
wouldn't even bother.

200
00:10:07,144 --> 00:10:10,080
Most poachers don't partially
gut the animal, either,

201
00:10:10,181 --> 00:10:13,116
unless they were after
something else.

202
00:10:13,217 --> 00:10:15,785
You mind if I
take a look at this elk?

203
00:10:15,886 --> 00:10:17,721
Yeah.

204
00:10:17,822 --> 00:10:20,523
Yeah, just as I suspected.

205
00:10:20,624 --> 00:10:22,559
Pancreas is missing.

206
00:10:22,660 --> 00:10:25,996
That would also explain
why the poacher took the head.

207
00:10:26,097 --> 00:10:28,531
He wanted antler velvet.

208
00:10:28,632 --> 00:10:30,600
Not following you, Omar.

209
00:10:30,701 --> 00:10:32,669
You ever hear of elk velvetine?

210
00:10:32,770 --> 00:10:35,005
I've heard of antler velvet,
but not velvetine.

211
00:10:35,106 --> 00:10:38,108
It's one of those new-age
Chinese supplements.

212
00:10:38,209 --> 00:10:41,277
Elk pancreas and antler velvet

213
00:10:41,379 --> 00:10:44,280
are the two main ingredients
you need to make the stuff.

214
00:10:44,382 --> 00:10:46,216
You saying this hunter
was killing elk

215
00:10:46,317 --> 00:10:48,084
for its medicinal properties?

216
00:10:48,185 --> 00:10:50,587
Well, there's a big, big market
in herbal medicines

217
00:10:50,688 --> 00:10:52,188
if you can find
the raw materials.

218
00:10:52,289 --> 00:10:56,760
These Chinese companies
hire a few hunters to --

219
00:10:56,861 --> 00:10:59,996
well, kind of like
medical mercenaries.

220
00:11:00,097 --> 00:11:02,565
These guys go all over the world
killing animals

221
00:11:02,666 --> 00:11:04,901
just so these companies
can make their remedies.

222
00:11:05,002 --> 00:11:07,670
Mm.

223
00:11:07,772 --> 00:11:10,140
How do these Chinese companies
find their poachers?

224
00:11:10,241 --> 00:11:12,642
Wait a minute.

225
00:11:12,743 --> 00:11:14,878
I know how one guy tried.

226
00:11:14,979 --> 00:11:17,714
About a month ago,
I had a Chinese guy

227
00:11:17,815 --> 00:11:20,316
on one of my trips --
Mr. Chen.

228
00:11:20,418 --> 00:11:22,719
Couldn't shoot worth a damn,

229
00:11:22,820 --> 00:11:26,156
but he sure seemed keen on
killing an elk.

230
00:11:26,257 --> 00:11:28,258
Even offered me some cash
to do it for him.

231
00:11:28,359 --> 00:11:30,293
What did you tell him?

232
00:11:30,394 --> 00:11:33,596
No, of course.

233
00:11:33,697 --> 00:11:37,934
Well, looks like
someone said yes.

234
00:11:42,539 --> 00:11:44,504
Hey, punk.
How you feeling?

235
00:11:44,606 --> 00:11:46,573
Cady: The same as I was
a few hours ago.

236
00:11:46,674 --> 00:11:48,308
I'm fine, dad.

237
00:11:48,550 --> 00:11:51,386
Well, uh,
Henry gave me his cellphone,

238
00:11:51,487 --> 00:11:53,388
so I thought
I'd give you a call,

239
00:11:53,489 --> 00:11:55,022
see if you needed anything.

240
00:11:55,124 --> 00:11:57,164
Don't worry about me.
You have plenty on your plate.

241
00:11:57,192 --> 00:11:59,660
Ruby stopped by earlier
and told me everything.

242
00:11:59,762 --> 00:12:01,462
Sounds crazy.

243
00:12:01,563 --> 00:12:03,798
Okay, uh, I'll call you later,

244
00:12:03,899 --> 00:12:05,900
or you can call me 'cause, um,

245
00:12:06,001 --> 00:12:07,902
I got a cellphone now.

246
00:12:08,003 --> 00:12:10,671
Uh, okay, you get some rest.

247
00:12:10,773 --> 00:12:13,374
Okay, I will.
I love you. Bye.

248
00:12:13,475 --> 00:12:14,809
Bye.

249
00:12:14,910 --> 00:12:16,744
[ Phone slams ]

250
00:12:19,948 --> 00:12:20,982
What?

251
00:12:21,083 --> 00:12:23,117
You had to
give him your cellphone?

252
00:12:25,921 --> 00:12:28,189
Ruby.
Ruby: Hi, Walt.

253
00:12:30,592 --> 00:12:32,660
Lee.

254
00:12:32,761 --> 00:12:35,463
I didn't think there was
much hope left for him.

255
00:12:35,564 --> 00:12:38,533
Oh, I think there's
a little life left in him.

256
00:12:38,634 --> 00:12:41,436
Try and take it easy on him, though.
Yeah. Thanks.

257
00:12:41,537 --> 00:12:43,057
Show me the bill
when you get a chance.

258
00:12:43,105 --> 00:12:44,539
Yeah, no problem.

259
00:12:44,640 --> 00:12:46,040
Want me to
hang him back up for you?

260
00:12:46,141 --> 00:12:48,676
Sure. Thanks.

261
00:12:48,777 --> 00:12:50,945
This name that Omar
gave you -- Mr. Chen.

262
00:12:51,046 --> 00:12:53,414
It's got to be an alias.
This guy's a ghost.

263
00:12:53,515 --> 00:12:56,484
Paid Omar in cash, so there's
no way to trace his receipts.

264
00:12:56,585 --> 00:12:57,819
And the address
and the phone number

265
00:12:57,920 --> 00:12:59,053
that he listed
on the registry --

266
00:12:59,154 --> 00:13:00,421
they're fakes, as well.

267
00:13:00,522 --> 00:13:02,356
Omar give you
a physical description?

268
00:13:02,458 --> 00:13:03,858
Yeah, mm-hmm.

269
00:13:03,959 --> 00:13:05,593
It was useless.

270
00:13:05,694 --> 00:13:06,961
And politically incorrect.

271
00:13:07,062 --> 00:13:08,863
Walt!

272
00:13:08,964 --> 00:13:11,432
I found some information
on elk velvetine.

273
00:13:11,533 --> 00:13:14,802
Check in with the other
hunting outfitters in town,

274
00:13:14,903 --> 00:13:16,571
see if Chen
booked any trips with them

275
00:13:16,672 --> 00:13:19,540
or if he's got any
updated contact information.

276
00:13:19,641 --> 00:13:22,910
Also, question as many
of the guides as you can.

277
00:13:23,011 --> 00:13:25,313
If Chen hired any of them
to poach for him,

278
00:13:25,414 --> 00:13:26,747
that might be our killer.

279
00:13:26,849 --> 00:13:28,449
All right, Ruby.
Shoot.

280
00:13:28,550 --> 00:13:30,084
Well, according to
these articles,

281
00:13:30,185 --> 00:13:32,854
the nearest place
you can buy velvetine is China.

282
00:13:32,955 --> 00:13:34,789
Now, you can get
a little bit online

283
00:13:34,890 --> 00:13:37,758
from those shady
Canadian pharmacies.

284
00:13:37,860 --> 00:13:39,694
But look --
a tiny little bottle

285
00:13:39,795 --> 00:13:41,829
is more expensive
than my car payments.

286
00:13:41,930 --> 00:13:44,050
So, if Mr. Chen found
a way to produce it in the U.S.,

287
00:13:44,099 --> 00:13:45,967
he could make a lot of money.

288
00:13:46,068 --> 00:13:48,002
Man, they use this stuff
for everything.

289
00:13:48,103 --> 00:13:50,571
Cancer patients
use it to re-grow muscle,

290
00:13:50,672 --> 00:13:52,740
eases arthritis in old people.

291
00:13:52,841 --> 00:13:54,742
They claim pro football players
are taking it

292
00:13:54,843 --> 00:13:56,577
instead of steroids.

293
00:13:56,678 --> 00:13:59,847
But there are other side effects.
Huh.

294
00:13:59,948 --> 00:14:03,551
Arrhythmia, severe cramping,

295
00:14:03,652 --> 00:14:06,087
increase of something called
wasting sickness,

296
00:14:06,188 --> 00:14:07,955
and high blood pressure.

297
00:14:08,056 --> 00:14:10,057
Huh.

298
00:14:14,563 --> 00:14:16,664
Thank you.

299
00:14:16,765 --> 00:14:18,432
[ Sighs ]

300
00:14:18,534 --> 00:14:20,801
Get some rest.

301
00:14:20,903 --> 00:14:23,671
Thought you guys could use
some new reading material.

302
00:14:23,772 --> 00:14:25,573
Already read through it twice.

303
00:14:25,674 --> 00:14:27,642
Well, thanks. That's --
that's awful nice.

304
00:14:27,743 --> 00:14:29,977
Uh, I'll give Troy first dibs.

305
00:14:30,078 --> 00:14:32,013
I was just
heading to the cafeteria.

306
00:14:32,114 --> 00:14:34,849
Why don't you stay
and talk some football?

307
00:14:37,185 --> 00:14:39,487
<i>Phil Steele's</i>
<i>College Football Preview.</i>

308
00:14:39,588 --> 00:14:40,788
Troy: Thank you.

309
00:14:42,958 --> 00:14:46,561
So, what schools
are you thinking about?

310
00:14:46,662 --> 00:14:48,429
I wanted to go to Oregon.

311
00:14:48,530 --> 00:14:50,798
I still do
if I ever get out of here.

312
00:14:50,899 --> 00:14:53,334
They even had scouts
looking at me last year.

313
00:14:53,435 --> 00:14:55,436
Oh.

314
00:14:55,537 --> 00:14:58,573
All that attention
from top programs,

315
00:14:58,674 --> 00:15:01,776
you probably put
a lot of pressure on yourself.

316
00:15:01,877 --> 00:15:03,644
Do what you got to do.

317
00:15:03,745 --> 00:15:06,113
Lot of boys in your position
tend to go the extra mile

318
00:15:06,214 --> 00:15:08,716
to impress the scouts.

319
00:15:08,817 --> 00:15:11,452
Extra workouts, protein diets.

320
00:15:11,553 --> 00:15:13,487
Some of them
even try supplements.

321
00:15:13,589 --> 00:15:18,125
You ever heard of
something called velvetine?

322
00:15:18,226 --> 00:15:22,063
Yeah. I heard, uh, pro and
college players use it, right?

323
00:15:22,164 --> 00:15:24,365
Yeah.

324
00:15:24,466 --> 00:15:26,334
How about you?

325
00:15:26,435 --> 00:15:28,703
No.

326
00:15:30,639 --> 00:15:32,406
Troy, the way I see things,

327
00:15:32,507 --> 00:15:34,609
your chances of
playing college ball

328
00:15:34,710 --> 00:15:37,511
are pretty slim if you don't
get out of this bed.

329
00:15:37,613 --> 00:15:39,447
Now, the wasting sickness
you have,

330
00:15:39,548 --> 00:15:42,350
velvetine can cause that.

331
00:15:42,451 --> 00:15:46,487
If you used it,
you should tell the doctors.

332
00:15:46,588 --> 00:15:48,889
They may be able to
help you play again.

333
00:15:51,426 --> 00:15:54,528
I just need to know
where you got it.

334
00:15:54,630 --> 00:15:56,931
There's at least 20
hunting guides in this town

335
00:15:57,032 --> 00:15:59,066
that need to be questioned.

336
00:15:59,167 --> 00:16:00,835
Don't you have to give, like,

337
00:16:00,936 --> 00:16:02,503
two weeks' notice or something
if you're quitting?

338
00:16:02,604 --> 00:16:03,938
Branch: I don't know
what I'm doing yet.

339
00:16:04,039 --> 00:16:05,740
There's stuff
I need to figure out.

340
00:16:05,841 --> 00:16:07,575
So, while you're out
soul searching,

341
00:16:07,676 --> 00:16:09,076
I'm on my own?

342
00:16:09,177 --> 00:16:11,812
What can I say?

343
00:16:11,913 --> 00:16:13,814
You should've voted for me.

344
00:16:13,915 --> 00:16:15,082
Yeah, whatever.

345
00:16:15,183 --> 00:16:16,817
[ Cellphone beeps ]

346
00:16:18,620 --> 00:16:22,056
Hey. I'm, uh, looking for
the owner -- Rosco Wilkes.

347
00:16:22,157 --> 00:16:23,991
You found her.

348
00:16:24,993 --> 00:16:26,727
My dad wanted a boy.

349
00:16:26,828 --> 00:16:28,929
How can I help you?
Uh...

350
00:16:29,031 --> 00:16:30,791
How many hunting guides
do you have on staff?

351
00:16:30,799 --> 00:16:32,500
High season, six,

352
00:16:32,601 --> 00:16:34,602
but this time of year, ain't
that much hunting to guide,

353
00:16:34,703 --> 00:16:36,871
so I only got one --
Keith Dixon.

354
00:16:36,972 --> 00:16:38,706
He's up in the big horns.

355
00:16:38,807 --> 00:16:41,475
Left two days ago to scout
fishing holes for a client.

356
00:16:41,576 --> 00:16:43,344
He got a cellphone up there?

357
00:16:43,445 --> 00:16:46,313
He's got a radio in his truck.
Checks in at night.

358
00:16:46,415 --> 00:16:48,082
Is there some kind of trouble?

359
00:16:48,183 --> 00:16:49,884
[ Chuckles ]

360
00:16:49,985 --> 00:16:52,687
I'm gonna need some information
about a possible client.

361
00:16:52,788 --> 00:16:55,923
Did a Mr. Chen book
a hunting trip with you guys?

362
00:16:56,024 --> 00:16:58,659
Name doesn't sound familiar.

363
00:16:58,760 --> 00:17:01,028
Oh, is he one of these guys?

364
00:17:01,129 --> 00:17:04,532
You know, it would help
if I knew what he looked like.

365
00:17:04,633 --> 00:17:07,568
I could check the registry,
see if we got any record of him.

366
00:17:07,669 --> 00:17:10,004
That'd be great.
Thanks.

367
00:17:14,142 --> 00:17:15,710
[ Whistle blows ]

368
00:17:15,811 --> 00:17:17,578
[ Indistinct shouting ]

369
00:17:19,981 --> 00:17:21,941
[ Whistle blows ]
Hargis: It's a shame about Troy.

370
00:17:21,983 --> 00:17:23,718
Kid with natural talent
like that,

371
00:17:23,819 --> 00:17:25,586
as a coach,
you're lucky if you see that

372
00:17:25,687 --> 00:17:27,855
four, maybe five times
in your career.

373
00:17:27,956 --> 00:17:29,657
Could've played
Division-I ball.

374
00:17:29,758 --> 00:17:32,059
He could've taken you with him.

375
00:17:32,160 --> 00:17:35,696
A lot of high-school coaches
like a shot at a college job.

376
00:17:35,797 --> 00:17:37,498
If a player under you
is recruited

377
00:17:37,599 --> 00:17:39,800
into a
Division-I school,

378
00:17:39,901 --> 00:17:41,936
it stands out on your résumé.

379
00:17:42,037 --> 00:17:44,672
Troy said the scouts were
coming to take a look at him.

380
00:17:44,773 --> 00:17:46,707
You needed him to make
a good impression.

381
00:17:46,808 --> 00:17:48,809
So, what are you getting at,
sheriff?

382
00:17:48,910 --> 00:17:52,079
Troy's sickness is caused by
a performance supplement --

383
00:17:52,180 --> 00:17:54,381
stuff called velvetine.

384
00:17:54,483 --> 00:17:56,317
He said you were the one
that gave it to him.

385
00:17:56,418 --> 00:17:59,353
I'll have you know I run
a clean program, sheriff.

386
00:17:59,454 --> 00:18:01,055
I won't deny that
I'd like a college job,

387
00:18:01,123 --> 00:18:02,857
but I'm not risking
the one that I got.

388
00:18:02,958 --> 00:18:04,892
Doping players -- that's grounds
for immediate dismissal.

389
00:18:04,993 --> 00:18:07,061
I'm not trying to
get you fired, coach.

390
00:18:07,162 --> 00:18:08,629
I'm just looking for a man

391
00:18:08,730 --> 00:18:10,664
that's connected
to the velvetine.

392
00:18:10,766 --> 00:18:13,033
Do you know someone
named Mr. Chen?

393
00:18:13,135 --> 00:18:14,101
Never heard of him.

394
00:18:14,202 --> 00:18:16,971
I care about Troy.

395
00:18:17,072 --> 00:18:19,974
I wouldn't push
any kind of supplement on him.

396
00:18:20,075 --> 00:18:22,576
Why did Troy
say it was you, then?

397
00:18:22,677 --> 00:18:25,312
[ Sighs ]

398
00:18:25,413 --> 00:18:27,982
Maybe he was trying to
protect his father.

399
00:18:28,083 --> 00:18:29,483
Grant's a sideline dad.

400
00:18:29,584 --> 00:18:31,786
Sits in the stands
every practice, yelling.

401
00:18:31,887 --> 00:18:34,421
I had to ask him to leave
a few times.

402
00:18:34,523 --> 00:18:37,758
Grant would do anything
to make sure that Troy succeeds.

403
00:18:44,499 --> 00:18:45,633
Hey.

404
00:18:45,734 --> 00:18:47,935
So, it turns out
Mr. Chen booked trips

405
00:18:48,036 --> 00:18:50,738
with five different hunting
outfitters over the last few months.

406
00:18:50,839 --> 00:18:53,507
I talked to as many of
the guides as I could locate.

407
00:18:53,608 --> 00:18:55,743
A few of them admit that he asked
them to shoot elk out of season,

408
00:18:55,844 --> 00:18:57,678
but they all claim
they turned him down.

409
00:18:57,779 --> 00:18:59,613
What are the photos for?

410
00:18:59,714 --> 00:19:01,615
I'm at a dead end
trying to find this guy.

411
00:19:01,716 --> 00:19:03,417
He paid cash
to all the outfitters,

412
00:19:03,518 --> 00:19:05,986
listed the same
useless contact information.

413
00:19:06,087 --> 00:19:08,923
So, I called Omar

414
00:19:09,024 --> 00:19:11,659
to see if maybe he had
a picture of Chen

415
00:19:11,760 --> 00:19:13,027
from one of their
hunting trips.

416
00:19:13,128 --> 00:19:15,095
It would help us
to know what he looked like.

417
00:19:15,197 --> 00:19:18,465
Ah. And there he is.

418
00:19:18,550 --> 00:19:20,518
Top left.

419
00:19:20,635 --> 00:19:23,521
I know him.
Mr. Chen?

420
00:19:23,638 --> 00:19:27,308
No.

421
00:19:27,409 --> 00:19:30,511
But I know Grant Thayer.

422
00:19:38,088 --> 00:19:40,890
[ Sighs ]

423
00:19:40,991 --> 00:19:43,993
So.
[ Clears throat ]

424
00:19:45,429 --> 00:19:47,730
I heard that the doctors

425
00:19:47,831 --> 00:19:50,767
have a plan of attack
for treating Troy...

426
00:19:50,868 --> 00:19:52,702
now that they know
he was taking velvetine.

427
00:19:55,806 --> 00:19:58,474
Troy told me he got it from
Coach Hargis.

428
00:19:58,575 --> 00:20:01,978
I spoke to Hargis.
He said it wasn't him.

429
00:20:02,079 --> 00:20:04,714
He thinks
it was someone else --

430
00:20:04,815 --> 00:20:06,716
someone close to Troy.

431
00:20:12,222 --> 00:20:14,657
You just want the best
for your kids.

432
00:20:14,758 --> 00:20:17,660
Want to give them
every advantage.

433
00:20:20,130 --> 00:20:21,931
I thought the stuff
was all-natural.

434
00:20:22,032 --> 00:20:24,467
I had no idea

435
00:20:24,568 --> 00:20:27,437
it could have
side effects like this.

436
00:20:27,538 --> 00:20:29,972
Where did you get
the velvetine?

437
00:20:32,543 --> 00:20:36,512
I learned about it from
some guy on a hunting trip.

438
00:20:41,585 --> 00:20:43,719
This man?

439
00:20:43,821 --> 00:20:45,655
Mr. Chen.

440
00:20:47,491 --> 00:20:48,724
[ Sighs ]

441
00:20:48,826 --> 00:20:51,494
He was going on
and on about it.

442
00:20:51,595 --> 00:20:54,864
When I heard the scouts
were coming,

443
00:20:54,965 --> 00:20:58,568
I-I called Chen

444
00:20:58,669 --> 00:21:01,771
and bought as much of the stuff
as he would sell me.

445
00:21:05,909 --> 00:21:09,479
Troy wanted this
more than anything...

446
00:21:09,580 --> 00:21:11,781
and I just wanted to help him.

447
00:21:14,117 --> 00:21:17,753
So, you have a way of
contacting Mr. Chen, then?

448
00:21:27,130 --> 00:21:30,600
You looking for Grant Thayer?

449
00:21:30,701 --> 00:21:33,135
Yes.

450
00:21:33,237 --> 00:21:36,672
Means you're Mr. Chen.

451
00:21:36,773 --> 00:21:39,375
You're a hard man to find.

452
00:21:39,476 --> 00:21:41,410
Now I know why.

453
00:21:41,512 --> 00:21:43,012
Jonathan Ling.

454
00:21:43,113 --> 00:21:45,581
You're a scientist?

455
00:21:45,682 --> 00:21:47,683
Engineer, actually.

456
00:21:47,784 --> 00:21:49,886
Coalage hired me
for a special project --

457
00:21:49,987 --> 00:21:53,689
converting coal to liquid gas,
which we sell to China.

458
00:21:53,790 --> 00:21:56,993
How's your company feel
about your side business?

459
00:21:57,094 --> 00:21:59,529
Jonathan: I'm not sure
I know what you mean.

460
00:21:59,630 --> 00:22:01,564
Selling velvetine.

461
00:22:01,665 --> 00:22:03,966
Why should they care?
I've done nothing illegal.

462
00:22:04,067 --> 00:22:05,902
I make many trips to China.

463
00:22:06,003 --> 00:22:08,070
Velvetine is made and sold
legally there.

464
00:22:08,171 --> 00:22:11,541
And I bring back small amounts
that the custom laws allow.

465
00:22:11,642 --> 00:22:15,378
I might charge my customers
a little bit extra for it here,

466
00:22:15,479 --> 00:22:17,980
but I'm simply obeying
the laws of supply and demand.

467
00:22:18,081 --> 00:22:20,383
I guess that high demand
is the reason

468
00:22:20,484 --> 00:22:22,718
you started
harvesting ingredients here --

469
00:22:22,819 --> 00:22:26,022
making velvetine yourself,
which is illegal.

470
00:22:26,123 --> 00:22:29,091
You went on hunting trips
over several months.

471
00:22:29,192 --> 00:22:30,993
A few of the outfitters said

472
00:22:31,094 --> 00:22:33,963
you offered them money
to kill elk out of season,

473
00:22:34,064 --> 00:22:35,731
and the trips stopped.

474
00:22:35,832 --> 00:22:37,733
Which probably means you found

475
00:22:37,834 --> 00:22:39,602
someone
willing to hunt for you.

476
00:22:39,703 --> 00:22:41,437
Or it could simply mean that

477
00:22:41,538 --> 00:22:42,972
my workload got a little hectic

478
00:22:43,073 --> 00:22:45,808
and I no longer have time
to take vacations.

479
00:22:45,909 --> 00:22:48,444
So, it's just
a coincidence that, uh,

480
00:22:48,545 --> 00:22:51,414
around the time
you stopped taking vacations,

481
00:22:51,515 --> 00:22:53,382
a hunter started slaying elk

482
00:22:53,483 --> 00:22:55,985
and taking the exact parts
you need to make velvetine.

483
00:22:56,086 --> 00:22:59,455
You have actual proof
that I hired this hunter?

484
00:22:59,556 --> 00:23:01,591
Not yet.

485
00:23:01,692 --> 00:23:03,593
Looks like this hunter
also killed

486
00:23:03,694 --> 00:23:05,561
a young man
named Connor Redding.

487
00:23:05,662 --> 00:23:09,732
He's a game warden
who stumbled on the operation.

488
00:23:09,833 --> 00:23:13,336
And when I find this hunter,
it's only a matter of time

489
00:23:13,437 --> 00:23:16,038
before he tells me about
your involvement,

490
00:23:16,139 --> 00:23:19,542
and you'll be implicated
in first-degree murder.

491
00:23:19,643 --> 00:23:21,978
I'm sorry I can't be of help,
sheriff.

492
00:23:22,079 --> 00:23:23,980
I have no operation.

493
00:23:24,081 --> 00:23:26,949
I'm just an engineer who,
on occasion,

494
00:23:27,050 --> 00:23:30,987
legally imports a product
for a few select clients.

495
00:23:33,123 --> 00:23:35,858
[ Music ]

496
00:23:38,829 --> 00:23:42,064
3:00 on a Tuesday
and you are not at work?

497
00:23:42,165 --> 00:23:44,367
Looking to drown your sorrows?

498
00:23:44,468 --> 00:23:48,170
[ Sighs ] Work is
sort of why I'm here.

499
00:23:50,173 --> 00:23:52,375
I need your advice
about something.

500
00:23:52,476 --> 00:23:55,411
You have got to be kidding me.

501
00:23:55,512 --> 00:23:56,979
Given everything that's happened
with the election,

502
00:23:57,080 --> 00:23:59,148
I'm in kind of a tough spot.

503
00:24:01,018 --> 00:24:03,119
I cannot pretend
to feel sorry for you.

504
00:24:07,124 --> 00:24:09,992
So, I never came up
with a backup plan

505
00:24:10,093 --> 00:24:11,694
in case I lost the election.

506
00:24:11,795 --> 00:24:14,697
Why not work for your father?

507
00:24:14,798 --> 00:24:17,433
Not an option.

508
00:24:17,534 --> 00:24:19,769
You <i>want</i> to work for Walt?

509
00:24:21,705 --> 00:24:23,906
I don't know if it matters
what I want.

510
00:24:27,444 --> 00:24:30,479
So, what advice
do you need from me?

511
00:24:30,580 --> 00:24:33,349
You've known him the longest.

512
00:24:33,450 --> 00:24:36,185
Is Walt the kind of man
who holds a grudge?

513
00:24:38,822 --> 00:24:42,692
The first time I met Walt,
we were in sixth grade.

514
00:24:42,793 --> 00:24:45,027
I was ahead of him in line
for the drinking fountain.

515
00:24:45,128 --> 00:24:47,430
When I took a drink,

516
00:24:47,531 --> 00:24:49,465
my lips touched the faucet.

517
00:24:49,566 --> 00:24:52,401
Walt called me out,
told me not to do that.

518
00:24:52,502 --> 00:24:54,737
I reacted as any
rational Indian kid would.

519
00:24:54,838 --> 00:24:56,672
I turned around
and punched him.

520
00:24:56,773 --> 00:24:58,574
After the principal
pulled us apart,

521
00:24:58,675 --> 00:25:00,076
he asked why we were fighting.

522
00:25:00,177 --> 00:25:01,844
I told him
it was a matter of honor.

523
00:25:01,945 --> 00:25:03,979
Walt did not want to
share the drinking fountain

524
00:25:04,081 --> 00:25:05,715
with a dirty Indian.

525
00:25:05,816 --> 00:25:07,983
But then Walt explained

526
00:25:08,085 --> 00:25:09,852
he was simply
trying to warn me.

527
00:25:09,953 --> 00:25:11,687
People have germs,

528
00:25:11,788 --> 00:25:15,491
and putting my lips on a faucet
is a good way to get sick.

529
00:25:17,527 --> 00:25:20,896
What's your point?

530
00:25:20,997 --> 00:25:24,033
I challenged Walt
without provocation.

531
00:25:24,134 --> 00:25:25,901
He could've hated me for it.

532
00:25:26,002 --> 00:25:29,371
Instead, we have been friends
for 38 years.

533
00:25:29,473 --> 00:25:34,009
If nothing else,
Walt believes in second chances.

534
00:25:44,755 --> 00:25:45,988
Hey.

535
00:25:46,089 --> 00:25:48,124
Taxidermist -- Lee Rosky --
just called.

536
00:25:48,225 --> 00:25:50,993
A guy named Keith Dixon came in and
asked him to mount an elk head.

537
00:25:51,094 --> 00:25:54,663
Turns out that Keith Dixon is one of the
guys that Chen booked a hunting trip with,

538
00:25:54,765 --> 00:25:56,966
only I didn't get to talk to him because
his boss said he was up in the mountains.

539
00:25:57,067 --> 00:25:58,968
He still at Lee's now?
No.

540
00:25:59,069 --> 00:26:01,036
Lee refused to stuff the head,
so the guy bolted.

541
00:26:01,138 --> 00:26:04,006
But I did get an address
from his boss.

542
00:26:08,678 --> 00:26:11,046
Check the back of the house.

543
00:26:20,857 --> 00:26:23,692
Open up!
Sheriff's department!

544
00:26:27,497 --> 00:26:29,999
[ Sniffing ]

545
00:26:36,773 --> 00:26:38,641
[ Sniffs, sighs ]

546
00:26:40,443 --> 00:26:42,545
Vic: Walt!

547
00:26:45,515 --> 00:26:47,650
Velvet's been scraped off.

548
00:26:47,751 --> 00:26:50,085
It looks like the head
that goes to our elk body.

549
00:26:50,187 --> 00:26:52,421
It's got to be the same one.

550
00:26:52,522 --> 00:26:54,123
I'll call the judge,
get a warrant.

551
00:26:54,224 --> 00:26:55,825
We don't need a warrant.

552
00:27:19,516 --> 00:27:21,016
Guy's got
a lot of animal parts,

553
00:27:21,117 --> 00:27:23,152
but they're all on the wall.

554
00:27:28,091 --> 00:27:30,492
[ Thud ]
[ Doorknob clatters ]

555
00:27:48,778 --> 00:27:50,613
[ Sighs ]

556
00:27:54,718 --> 00:27:56,886
Antler velvet.

557
00:28:00,123 --> 00:28:02,992
[ Sighs ]

558
00:28:03,093 --> 00:28:05,160
Is this what I think it is?

559
00:28:05,262 --> 00:28:06,829
Pancreas.

560
00:28:06,930 --> 00:28:09,899
Well, we found Keith's stash.

561
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:13,068
Now we just have to
go find Keith.

562
00:28:21,695 --> 00:28:24,596
[ Sighs ]
Why couldn't Vic come?

563
00:28:24,698 --> 00:28:26,243
Lighten the mood in here a bit.

564
00:28:26,835 --> 00:28:28,269
If I recall,

565
00:28:28,370 --> 00:28:30,972
last time Vic
went hunting with you, Omar,

566
00:28:31,073 --> 00:28:33,307
she got shot.

567
00:28:33,409 --> 00:28:35,843
[ Chuckles ]

568
00:28:35,944 --> 00:28:37,845
And why did we have to
bring him?

569
00:28:37,946 --> 00:28:41,115
Walt: Well, he's
the best tracker I know.

570
00:28:41,216 --> 00:28:43,117
I'll be the judge of that.

571
00:28:44,686 --> 00:28:47,889
Okay, so you said Keith
was heading to piedmont falls?

572
00:28:47,990 --> 00:28:51,192
According to his boss,
he was scouting fishing holes.

573
00:28:51,293 --> 00:28:55,696
Destination --
Piedmont Falls, Wyoming.

574
00:28:55,798 --> 00:28:57,265
[ GPS beeps ]

575
00:28:57,366 --> 00:28:59,901
He probably entered in
right there.

576
00:29:00,002 --> 00:29:01,602
Though there's
no fishing worth a damn

577
00:29:01,703 --> 00:29:03,171
anywhere near here.

578
00:29:03,272 --> 00:29:05,373
But it is near
an elk migration route.

579
00:29:10,779 --> 00:29:14,148
Looks like we found our man.

580
00:29:14,249 --> 00:29:17,718
Or at least his truck.

581
00:29:19,721 --> 00:29:21,923
Walt: You said
Keith worked for you?

582
00:29:22,024 --> 00:29:24,692
Omar: Yeah.
Till I had to fire him.

583
00:29:24,793 --> 00:29:26,227
Henry: Why?

584
00:29:26,328 --> 00:29:27,995
Found out
he took a few guys out

585
00:29:28,097 --> 00:29:29,797
on a special
hunting expedition.

586
00:29:29,898 --> 00:29:32,133
They offered him money
to shoot a bald eagle,

587
00:29:32,234 --> 00:29:33,868
and he took it.

588
00:29:33,969 --> 00:29:36,904
Killing animals for money
is one thing.

589
00:29:37,005 --> 00:29:39,974
Stabbing a man to death's
another story.

590
00:29:40,075 --> 00:29:42,043
You think Keith could've
killed Connor Redding?

591
00:29:43,979 --> 00:29:46,047
Yeah, I do.

592
00:29:47,950 --> 00:29:49,750
Elk tracks.

593
00:29:52,688 --> 00:29:54,722
Look at this.

594
00:29:56,692 --> 00:29:59,227
Salt lick.

595
00:29:59,328 --> 00:30:01,288
Think fishing and game
could've put this out here?

596
00:30:01,330 --> 00:30:02,663
No.

597
00:30:02,764 --> 00:30:04,165
But it sounds like Keith.

598
00:30:04,266 --> 00:30:06,200
Some guys track.

599
00:30:06,301 --> 00:30:08,169
Keith was always
a shortcut artist.

600
00:30:08,270 --> 00:30:10,171
He puts out salt licks
to attract the elk,

601
00:30:10,272 --> 00:30:11,772
then hunkers down somewhere

602
00:30:11,874 --> 00:30:13,354
and waits for his prey
to come to him.

603
00:30:13,442 --> 00:30:16,777
That tree line's the best
vantage point for a hunter.

604
00:30:16,879 --> 00:30:19,647
Keith's probably
hiding in there right now.

605
00:30:19,748 --> 00:30:22,717
We need to get moving.

606
00:30:27,122 --> 00:30:28,823
Easy, Omar.

607
00:30:28,924 --> 00:30:30,324
I <i>am</i> easy.

608
00:30:30,425 --> 00:30:32,760
Till I find Keith.

609
00:30:32,861 --> 00:30:35,129
Do not be in such a hurry!
[ Screams ]

610
00:30:35,230 --> 00:30:37,999
Henry?! Henry!
[ Screams, groans ]

611
00:30:38,100 --> 00:30:40,201
[ Groans ]
O.I.T.

612
00:30:40,302 --> 00:30:42,203
What the hell's --
Old Indian Trick.

613
00:30:42,304 --> 00:30:44,639
[ Sighs ]
But you <i>are</i> an Indian.

614
00:30:44,740 --> 00:30:46,073
I am Cheyenne.

615
00:30:46,175 --> 00:30:47,975
This is an Apache death trap,

616
00:30:48,076 --> 00:30:50,344
and if you were not distracting
me, my leg would not be

617
00:30:50,445 --> 00:30:52,346
stuck in a hole
with sharp wooden stakes!

618
00:30:52,447 --> 00:30:55,049
The animal's leg
goes in easy enough.

619
00:30:55,150 --> 00:30:57,685
Yes, but you try to pull it out,
it messes you up.

620
00:30:57,786 --> 00:31:00,221
[ Grunts ]
Give me a hand here, Omar.

621
00:31:00,322 --> 00:31:01,956
Before guns, the hunters

622
00:31:02,057 --> 00:31:04,158
used these traps
to bring down big game...

623
00:31:04,259 --> 00:31:05,793
[ Grunts ]
...Easy.

624
00:31:05,894 --> 00:31:07,929
Well, that sounds like Keith.

625
00:31:08,030 --> 00:31:09,764
[ Grunts ]

626
00:31:09,865 --> 00:31:12,833
He's probably nearby.

627
00:31:12,935 --> 00:31:15,870
Jeff: We ran that print you sent
us through the DCI computer.

628
00:31:15,971 --> 00:31:17,672
Got a hit right away.

629
00:31:17,773 --> 00:31:19,307
Guy's name is David Ridges.

630
00:31:19,408 --> 00:31:20,875
He got any kind of record?

631
00:31:20,976 --> 00:31:22,743
Yeah, at least five
prior arrests

632
00:31:22,844 --> 00:31:24,812
in Montana and Wyoming,
mostly assaults.

633
00:31:24,913 --> 00:31:26,881
I got his last-known address
here if you want it.

634
00:31:26,982 --> 00:31:28,316
I do.
Can you e-mail it to me?

635
00:31:28,417 --> 00:31:29,717
Sure thing.

636
00:31:40,262 --> 00:31:42,697
[ Elk calling ]

637
00:31:57,879 --> 00:32:01,616
[ Calling continues ]

638
00:32:01,717 --> 00:32:03,284
[ Leaves rustle ]

639
00:32:06,855 --> 00:32:08,256
[ Elk call sounds ]

640
00:32:08,357 --> 00:32:10,258
What the...

641
00:32:10,359 --> 00:32:12,760
[ Gun cocks ]

642
00:32:12,861 --> 00:32:14,795
Don't move, Keith.

643
00:32:14,896 --> 00:32:16,664
Oh, come on, Walt.

644
00:32:16,765 --> 00:32:18,032
Let him run.

645
00:32:18,133 --> 00:32:20,768
I love a moving target.

646
00:32:26,580 --> 00:32:27,880
[ Door opens ]

647
00:32:27,981 --> 00:32:30,716
Vic, get Devin Gaines
on the phone.

648
00:32:31,312 --> 00:32:33,347
Tell him we got Keith Dixon
in custody.

649
00:32:33,448 --> 00:32:35,382
[ Clears throat ]
Mm-hmm.

650
00:32:35,483 --> 00:32:39,119
I'll get, uh, Mr. Dixon
settled into your office.

651
00:32:43,591 --> 00:32:45,459
Hey, Walt.

652
00:32:59,140 --> 00:33:01,308
Does this mean
you still work here?

653
00:33:01,409 --> 00:33:04,311
I guess it does.

654
00:33:06,280 --> 00:33:07,547
Okay, then.

655
00:33:15,556 --> 00:33:18,225
You want to try and slap some
poaching charges on me,

656
00:33:18,326 --> 00:33:20,160
be my guest.

657
00:33:20,261 --> 00:33:22,863
You can't ever prove that
I set any of those traps.

658
00:33:22,964 --> 00:33:25,098
Walt: No need.

659
00:33:25,199 --> 00:33:27,234
Considering all the, uh,

660
00:33:27,335 --> 00:33:29,302
antler velvet and pancreas

661
00:33:29,404 --> 00:33:31,238
we've already taken
from your house,

662
00:33:31,339 --> 00:33:34,574
I say we'd got more than enough
evidence to charge you.

663
00:33:34,675 --> 00:33:36,376
You guys went to my house?

664
00:33:36,477 --> 00:33:38,445
All those body parts.

665
00:33:38,546 --> 00:33:41,348
Devin Gaines said that's
at least 15 years in prison.

666
00:33:41,449 --> 00:33:43,209
I wasn't killing those elk
for me, all right?

667
00:33:43,217 --> 00:33:44,951
I was hunting for someone else,

668
00:33:45,053 --> 00:33:47,454
and he was using those parts
to make medicine or something.

669
00:33:47,555 --> 00:33:50,123
Was this the someone else?

670
00:33:50,224 --> 00:33:54,428
He either goes by the name
Mr. Chen or Jonathan Ling.

671
00:33:54,529 --> 00:33:56,863
You ease up on my charges,

672
00:33:56,964 --> 00:33:58,965
and I'll write a novel
about the guy.

673
00:33:59,067 --> 00:34:01,935
Huh. Okay.

674
00:34:02,036 --> 00:34:05,906
May be able to cut some years
off your poaching sentence,

675
00:34:06,007 --> 00:34:07,908
but you're still
looking at a life term

676
00:34:08,009 --> 00:34:09,443
for killing Connor Redding.

677
00:34:09,544 --> 00:34:12,512
Connor Redding? What are you --
what are you talking --

678
00:34:12,613 --> 00:34:15,348
He's the game warden
we found stabbed...

679
00:34:15,450 --> 00:34:18,051
next to a beheaded elk.

680
00:34:18,152 --> 00:34:20,287
Now, whoever killed Connor

681
00:34:20,388 --> 00:34:23,023
also killed that elk
and took its head.

682
00:34:23,124 --> 00:34:24,891
We found that head
in your dumpster.

683
00:34:24,992 --> 00:34:26,293
Whoa, okay.

684
00:34:26,394 --> 00:34:28,462
Hold on a second here.
Okay?

685
00:34:28,563 --> 00:34:30,263
The first thing you learn

686
00:34:30,364 --> 00:34:33,100
is never dump illegal parts
where anyone can find them,

687
00:34:33,201 --> 00:34:35,002
and I definitely wouldn't
leave a rotting head

688
00:34:35,103 --> 00:34:36,603
outside my own house --
I mean, come on, guys.

689
00:34:36,704 --> 00:34:38,338
Really, how stupid
do you think I am?

690
00:34:38,439 --> 00:34:40,340
Stupid enough
to ask a taxidermist

691
00:34:40,441 --> 00:34:41,575
to stuff it for you.

692
00:34:41,676 --> 00:34:43,176
[ Scoffs ] Come on.

693
00:34:43,277 --> 00:34:45,378
Okay, y'all were
at my house, right?

694
00:34:45,480 --> 00:34:47,347
You saw the 10-point buck
on the wall.

695
00:34:47,448 --> 00:34:49,149
That's a head worth mounting,
okay?

696
00:34:49,250 --> 00:34:52,319
Why would I waste money
stuffing a puny head like this?

697
00:34:52,420 --> 00:34:54,154
Huh?

698
00:34:54,255 --> 00:34:57,324
And who told you that I brought
that head to the taxidermist?

699
00:35:00,128 --> 00:35:03,296
Sheriff's department!

700
00:35:03,397 --> 00:35:05,031
[ Knock on door ]

701
00:35:05,133 --> 00:35:08,001
Lee. We need to talk.

702
00:35:10,471 --> 00:35:13,573
Sorry. Couldn't
get to the door quick enough.

703
00:35:13,674 --> 00:35:16,109
I don't move as fast
as I used to.

704
00:35:16,210 --> 00:35:18,211
I'm sorry.
I was looking for Lee.

705
00:35:18,312 --> 00:35:21,181
He left about an hour ago to
make some firewood deliveries.

706
00:35:21,282 --> 00:35:23,016
I'm his wife, Bonnie.

707
00:35:23,117 --> 00:35:24,584
[ Tea kettle whistles ]

708
00:35:24,685 --> 00:35:26,453
I was just
making myself some tea.

709
00:35:26,554 --> 00:35:28,355
Lee should be home shortly.

710
00:35:28,456 --> 00:35:30,924
Come have a cup while you wait.

711
00:35:31,025 --> 00:35:33,560
[ Whistling continues ]

712
00:35:37,331 --> 00:35:39,633
Please, um,
let me get that for you.

713
00:35:39,734 --> 00:35:41,568
Oh, thank you.

714
00:35:41,669 --> 00:35:44,104
The tea's already in the pot,

715
00:35:44,205 --> 00:35:46,373
and there's another cup
on the counter there.

716
00:35:46,474 --> 00:35:47,941
[ Whistling stops ]
You take a seat.

717
00:35:48,042 --> 00:35:50,377
Allow me.
Okeydokey.

718
00:35:50,478 --> 00:35:53,647
[ Water pouring ]

719
00:35:55,917 --> 00:35:57,551
There you go.

720
00:35:59,320 --> 00:36:03,990
I was so sorry to hear about
your wife's passing.

721
00:36:04,091 --> 00:36:06,359
You two knew one another?

722
00:36:06,460 --> 00:36:09,262
A little.
We were chemo buddies.

723
00:36:12,366 --> 00:36:15,101
She never mentioned you.
It was a group of us.

724
00:36:15,203 --> 00:36:18,471
We kind of
formed a private club.

725
00:36:18,573 --> 00:36:21,508
Martha would always say,
"Admission is free

726
00:36:21,609 --> 00:36:23,510
'cause we've all
paid our dues."

727
00:36:23,611 --> 00:36:25,712
[ Chuckles ]

728
00:36:27,949 --> 00:36:31,351
I was surprised
she was taken so quickly.

729
00:36:31,452 --> 00:36:35,956
Considering what I'm going
through at this stage,

730
00:36:36,057 --> 00:36:39,226
I'm grateful she was spared
this kind of pain.

731
00:36:42,129 --> 00:36:45,198
What kind of treatment do they have you on?
None.

732
00:36:45,299 --> 00:36:49,836
The last round of radiation
almost did me in.

733
00:36:49,937 --> 00:36:51,438
It's funny.

734
00:36:51,539 --> 00:36:54,174
You take medicine
trying to kill a disease,

735
00:36:54,275 --> 00:36:56,509
and it almost kills you.

736
00:36:56,611 --> 00:36:59,279
I told Lee, I said, no more.

737
00:36:59,380 --> 00:37:03,283
No more doctors, no more
hospitals, no more medicine.

738
00:37:03,384 --> 00:37:07,454
So, uh...
what's all this, then?

739
00:37:07,555 --> 00:37:11,157
Just herbal remedies.

740
00:37:11,259 --> 00:37:14,194
You familiar with a supplement
called velvetine?

741
00:37:14,295 --> 00:37:16,529
Yeah, Lee got it for me

742
00:37:16,631 --> 00:37:18,365
after he read about it
on the Internet.

743
00:37:18,466 --> 00:37:21,935
Supposed to be
some kind of miracle cure.

744
00:37:22,036 --> 00:37:24,471
I don't know if it's
making me any better,

745
00:37:24,572 --> 00:37:27,240
but it makes him feel better
when I take it.

746
00:37:27,341 --> 00:37:29,042
Do you know
where he gets it from?

747
00:37:31,112 --> 00:37:33,146
[ Grunts ]
[ Dishes clatter ]

748
00:37:38,286 --> 00:37:39,519
[ Screams ]
Lee!

749
00:37:39,620 --> 00:37:43,290
One man's already dead,
Lee! [ Grunts ]

750
00:37:43,391 --> 00:37:45,425
Lee! Stop this!

751
00:37:45,526 --> 00:37:46,626
You listen to her.

752
00:37:48,062 --> 00:37:48,728
Stop.

753
00:37:51,265 --> 00:37:53,967
[ Whimpers ]

754
00:37:57,271 --> 00:38:00,807
Lee, what is going on here?

755
00:38:00,908 --> 00:38:02,042
Please tell me.

756
00:38:02,143 --> 00:38:04,044
He was trying to save you.

757
00:38:04,145 --> 00:38:05,845
What?

758
00:38:05,946 --> 00:38:07,447
[ Sighs ]

759
00:38:07,548 --> 00:38:10,984
I was just trying to
get your medicine for you.

760
00:38:11,085 --> 00:38:13,253
The velvetine.

761
00:38:13,354 --> 00:38:16,323
Keith Dixon came by my shop

762
00:38:16,424 --> 00:38:18,925
with a sample of the velvetine,

763
00:38:19,026 --> 00:38:21,161
and it worked.

764
00:38:21,262 --> 00:38:24,097
I could see the change in you
right away.

765
00:38:24,198 --> 00:38:27,901
But when we ran out, I...

766
00:38:28,002 --> 00:38:30,537
I couldn't afford it.

767
00:38:30,638 --> 00:38:33,273
I looked everywhere,
tried everything.

768
00:38:33,374 --> 00:38:35,975
And you couldn't stand by,

769
00:38:36,060 --> 00:38:39,245
let that disease win --
you had to fight it.

770
00:38:39,346 --> 00:38:41,614
So you decided to
make your own velvetine.

771
00:38:41,699 --> 00:38:44,217
But that game warden caught me.

772
00:38:44,318 --> 00:38:48,388
He was gonna take me in,
and that would've meant jail.

773
00:38:48,489 --> 00:38:52,292
So we fought.

774
00:38:52,393 --> 00:38:55,195
And I stabbed him.
[ Sobs ]

775
00:38:55,296 --> 00:38:57,197
I couldn't let him
take me away --

776
00:38:57,298 --> 00:38:59,833
not -- not with Bonnie
in her condition.

777
00:38:59,934 --> 00:39:02,402
It was either him or your wife.

778
00:39:02,503 --> 00:39:04,371
[ Voice breaking ] Yes.

779
00:39:06,273 --> 00:39:08,541
Lee, baby.

780
00:39:08,642 --> 00:39:11,978
I am not getting better.

781
00:39:12,079 --> 00:39:14,381
You have to let me go.

782
00:39:14,482 --> 00:39:16,950
You have to.

783
00:39:17,051 --> 00:39:20,353
[ Crying ]
No. No. I never will.

784
00:39:23,624 --> 00:39:26,259
Hey.

785
00:39:26,360 --> 00:39:29,362
I was beginning to
wonder about you.

786
00:39:29,463 --> 00:39:31,865
You disappeared for a bit.

787
00:39:31,966 --> 00:39:34,367
Been a little preoccupied.

788
00:39:34,468 --> 00:39:37,203
Did you know Cady Longmire
was in a car accident?

789
00:39:37,304 --> 00:39:40,340
She okay?

790
00:39:40,441 --> 00:39:43,376
She will be.

791
00:39:43,477 --> 00:39:46,212
But I've been looking into the
circumstances of the accident,

792
00:39:46,313 --> 00:39:48,982
and I found some odd things.

793
00:39:49,083 --> 00:39:51,251
First...I found

794
00:39:51,352 --> 00:39:54,187
a round puncture in the
side wall of a brand-new tire

795
00:39:54,288 --> 00:39:57,457
on the station wagon
that Cady was driving.

796
00:39:57,558 --> 00:40:00,493
Not the tread,
but the side wall,

797
00:40:00,594 --> 00:40:04,531
meaning someone
flattened that tire on purpose.

798
00:40:04,632 --> 00:40:07,567
Also lifted a fingerprint
off the car

799
00:40:07,668 --> 00:40:10,570
right above the rear-back
flat tire.

800
00:40:10,671 --> 00:40:14,174
Belongs to a guy named
David Ridges.

801
00:40:14,275 --> 00:40:16,342
Tried to visit him at home,
he wasn't there,

802
00:40:16,444 --> 00:40:19,379
but I did find an interesting
detail on his résumé.

803
00:40:19,480 --> 00:40:21,981
You found...

804
00:40:22,082 --> 00:40:26,286
that David works for me.

805
00:40:26,387 --> 00:40:28,221
Normally, I wouldn't
blink at that.

806
00:40:28,322 --> 00:40:30,089
You have a lot of employees,

807
00:40:30,191 --> 00:40:32,125
but then I remembered
what you said

808
00:40:32,226 --> 00:40:35,295
about retail politics.

809
00:40:35,396 --> 00:40:38,465
Getting more of
our own voters to the polls,

810
00:40:38,566 --> 00:40:42,435
keeping more of
the other guy's voters away.

811
00:40:42,536 --> 00:40:45,271
You didn't have anything to do
with Cady's accident, did you?

812
00:40:45,372 --> 00:40:48,541
You know, my people have had

813
00:40:48,642 --> 00:40:51,978
a bad couple of centuries.

814
00:40:52,079 --> 00:40:55,148
Some of us have learned that
to get by in the present,

815
00:40:55,249 --> 00:40:57,250
you need to let go of the past.

816
00:40:57,351 --> 00:41:01,387
In fact, I'd imagine that
I have already forgotten more

817
00:41:01,489 --> 00:41:04,324
than most people
will ever experience

818
00:41:04,425 --> 00:41:07,927
in their lives.

819
00:41:08,028 --> 00:41:12,332
My advice to you
would be to do the same.

820
00:41:12,433 --> 00:41:14,067
Don't look back.

821
00:41:14,168 --> 00:41:17,036
Could lead to real pain.

822
00:41:17,137 --> 00:41:19,939
It's better to keep your eyes

823
00:41:20,040 --> 00:41:22,642
down the road, my man,

824
00:41:22,743 --> 00:41:25,545
on your very bright future.

825
00:41:25,646 --> 00:41:28,581
Not really an answer, Jacob.

826
00:41:34,388 --> 00:41:37,123
I'll see you around.

827
00:41:42,263 --> 00:41:44,531
Favorite from the Busy Bee.

828
00:41:44,632 --> 00:41:46,366
Biscuits and gravy.

829
00:41:46,467 --> 00:41:48,134
Thank you.

830
00:41:52,540 --> 00:41:55,375
Have you gotten any sleep
in the last few days?

831
00:41:55,476 --> 00:41:58,278
I plan to.

832
00:41:58,379 --> 00:42:01,548
Things are starting to
settle down.

833
00:42:01,649 --> 00:42:05,285
Got a full team back
at the station again, so...

834
00:42:05,386 --> 00:42:07,587
decided to
keep your boyfriend on.

835
00:42:09,523 --> 00:42:11,958
He's not my boyfriend.

836
00:42:12,059 --> 00:42:15,361
I'm...
not sure what he is.

837
00:42:15,462 --> 00:42:18,331
Well, whatever.

838
00:42:18,432 --> 00:42:22,335
"Whatever"?
[ Chuckles ]

839
00:42:22,436 --> 00:42:25,738
I don't think I've ever heard you
say that word my entire life.

840
00:42:29,176 --> 00:42:32,445
I know I had some issues
with branch in the past, but...

841
00:42:32,546 --> 00:42:34,447
I got to let that go.

842
00:42:34,548 --> 00:42:39,218
I got to
let a lot of things go.

843
00:42:39,320 --> 00:42:41,487
Maybe I'm just
starting to mellow.

844
00:42:43,490 --> 00:42:46,392
I should
get hit by a car more often.

845
00:42:46,493 --> 00:42:48,628
No.

846
00:42:48,729 --> 00:42:51,230
Once was enough.

847
